Getting the data & making necessary changes¶

This section of the code starts by importing the necessary libraries for data manipulation, visualization, and machine learning. The pandas library is used to handle the dataset, while seaborn and matplotlib are employed to create visualizations. Numpy is imported for numerical operations, and scikit-learn provides functions for label encoding, scaling, splitting the dataset, and applying machine learning models like the decision tree classifier.

The Iris dataset is then loaded into a pandas DataFrame using pd.read_csv('Iris.csv'), and the first few rows of the dataset are displayed using Iris.head().

This shows the sepal and petal measurements for various Iris species (e.g., Iris-setosa). The code prepares the data for further analysis by confirming the dataset's structure and cleanliness. The next steps will involve preprocessing, model training, and performance evaluation, as suggested by the imported functions for model splitting and evaluation.

Train and Test Split¶

In [39]:
x = Iris.drop(["Species"], axis=1) 
y = Iris["Species"]
scaler = StandardScaler()
x_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(x)
# Update the train-test split to use normalized features
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x_scaled, y, test_size=0.25, random_state=42, stratify=y)

For the train-test split, I first separated the features and the target variable. The features (x) were obtained by dropping the 'Species' column from the DataFrame, while the target (y) was simply the 'Species' column. I then used StandardScaler() to normalize the features, which ensures that all features have the same scale, improving the performance and convergence of many machine learning models. The fit_transform() method was applied to scale the features (x_scaled).

After scaling, I split the dataset into training and test sets using the train_test_split() function. I set the test size to 0.25, meaning 25% of the data will be used for testing, while the remaining 75% will be used for training. The random_state=42 ensures reproducibility, and stratify=y ensures that the class distribution is preserved in both training and test sets. This step was essential for preparing the data for model training and evaluation, ensuring a balanced representation of each class in both sets.

Then to evaluate the performance of the model, I used cross-validation with a DecisionTreeClassifier. I specified random_state=42 to ensure consistent results. The cross_val_score() function was used to perform 5-fold cross-validation (cv=5) on the training data. This means that the training set was split into 5 parts, and the model was trained and evaluated on each of these parts, providing 5 separate accuracy scores.

The cross-validation scores were printed, along with the mean cross-validation score. The mean accuracy was about 0.93, indicating that the model performs quite well on average. Cross-validation helps provide a more robust measure of the model's performance by ensuring that the evaluation is not dependent on a single split of the data, reducing overfitting risks and providing a clearer picture of how the model generalizes.

Hyper-parameter Tuning¶

In [56]:
# Parameter grid for optimization
param_grid = {
    'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'],
    'max_depth': [None, 5, 10, 15],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4]
}

# GridSearchCV with cross-validation
grid_search = GridSearchCV(DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42), param_grid, cv=5, n_jobs=-1, scoring='accuracy')
grid_search.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Best parameters from GridSearch
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
print("Best Parameters:", best_params)

# Train the model using the best parameters
best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_
best_model.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Evaluate the optimized model
optimized_predictions = best_model.predict(x_test)
optimized_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, optimized_predictions)
print("Optimized Accuracy Score:", optimized_accuracy)

optimized_cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, optimized_predictions)
print("Optimized Confusion Matrix:\n", optimized_cm)

optimized_classification_error = 1 - optimized_accuracy
print("Optimized Classification Error:", optimized_classification_error)

# Plot the confusion matrix for the optimized model
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(optimized_cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Reds', cbar=False,
            xticklabels=['Setosa', 'Versicolor', 'Virginica'],
            yticklabels=['Setosa', 'Versicolor', 'Virginica'])
plt.title('Confusion Matrix (Optimized Model)')
plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')
plt.ylabel('True Label')
plt.show()

Best Parameters: {'criterion': 'gini', 'max_depth': None, 'min_samples_leaf': 1, 'min_samples_split': 5}
Optimized Accuracy Score: 0.9210526315789473
Optimized Confusion Matrix:
 [[12  0  0]
 [ 0 12  1]
 [ 0  2 11]]
Optimized Classification Error: 0.07894736842105265

To optimize the performance of my decision tree model, I used GridSearchCV to search over a grid of hyperparameters. I specified a parameter grid (param_grid) that included different values for 'criterion', 'max_depth', 'min_samples_split', and 'min_samples_leaf'. The GridSearchCV function was used to find the best combination of these parameters by performing cross-validation on the training data. After fitting the grid search, I obtained the best model parameters, which were {criterion: 'gini', max_depth: None, min_samples_leaf: 1, min_samples_split: 5}.

Using these best parameters, I trained a new model (best_model) and evaluated its performance. The optimized accuracy score improved to approximately 92.1%, and the classification error decreased to around 7.9%. The optimized confusion matrix shows that most classes were correctly classified, with only a few misclassifications involving 'versicolor' and 'virginica'. Visualizing this confusion matrix helped confirm that the optimized model had a better classification capability compared to the previous one, reducing errors between overlapping classes.

The confusion matrix for the optimized model was visualized using Seaborn's heatmap, with red shades representing the frequency of predictions in each category. From the confusion matrix, it's evident that all 'setosa' samples were correctly classified, similar to before. The model made only one mistake with the 'versicolor' class, misclassifying it as 'virginica', and two errors with 'virginica', which were classified as 'versicolor'. The reduced number of misclassifications compared to the initial model highlights the improvement brought by hyperparameter tuning, particularly in differentiating between the overlapping classes of 'versicolor' and 'virginica'.

For visualizing the decision tree, I used plot_tree() to generate a clear and interpretable visualization of my decision tree model. I set the figure size to (16, 12) for better readability, and included feature names and class names (Setosa, Versicolor, Virginica) for easy understanding. The decision tree plot provides a graphical representation of the splits at each node, including the conditions, Gini impurity values, and class labels.

The decision tree visualization provides an insight into how the model splits the dataset based on different features to classify each iris species (Setosa, Versicolor, Virginica). The root of the tree starts with Petal.Length, which is the most informative feature, used to make the first split. This split helps in differentiating Setosa from the other species since Setosa has distinctively smaller petal lengths.

As we move down the branches, further splits occur based on features like Petal.Width, Sepal.Length, and Sepal.Width. For instance, after separating Setosa, the next splits are primarily focused on distinguishing Versicolor from Virginica. Nodes in the tree show important information, such as Gini impurity (a measure of the impurity or heterogeneity at each split), the number of samples, and the value, which indicates the count of samples per class.

The leaves of the tree (nodes at the bottom) represent the final classification, where all samples belong to a single class, indicated by Gini of 0. The decision tree thus visually conveys the sequential feature splits that lead to each prediction, highlighting how petal and sepal characteristics are used to classify iris species step by step.

Results¶

The results demonstrated the effectiveness of using a Decision Tree classifier for classifying iris species. The initial model achieved a cross-validation accuracy of approximately 92.9%, with precision, recall, and F1 scores around the same value, indicating balanced performance across metrics. The confusion matrix revealed that the model had some difficulty distinguishing between 'versicolor' and 'virginica,' resulting in a few misclassifications.

After optimizing the hyperparameters using GridSearchCV, the model's accuracy improved to 92.1%, with a classification error of 7.9%. The optimized model made fewer mistakes in distinguishing between overlapping classes, as observed in the optimized confusion matrix. The Decision Tree visualization provided insight into how feature splits were made to classify different iris species, with the tree structure effectively differentiating 'setosa' while managing some overlap between 'versicolor' and 'virginica'.

Overall, the results illustrate the capability of Decision Tree models for classification tasks and the impact of hyperparameter tuning on model performance. Despite some limitations in differentiating similar classes, the model performed well, demonstrating a clear improvement after optimization.

Research¶

Throughout this project, I gained valuable insights into various machine learning techniques and tools that were previously unfamiliar to me. One of the key things I learned was how to plot violin plots. These plots were incredibly useful in visualizing the distribution of features across different classes, showing both the density and variability in an intuitive way. By understanding violin plots, I was able to better interpret how feature distributions differed among iris species.

Another significant learning was the application of the Label Encoder from scikit-learn. The Label Encoder helped in transforming categorical labels into numerical values, which is a crucial step when preparing data for machine learning models. This helped me understand how categorical data can be handled effectively in Python.

I also learned about feature scaling through the use of the StandardScaler. Scaling features is a vital preprocessing step to ensure that all features contribute equally to the model, especially when using algorithms sensitive to feature magnitude. By scaling the dataset, I ensured that none of the features dominated the learning process due to larger numerical values.

The Decision Tree Classifier was another new concept for me. I explored how to use decision trees for classification tasks, including how to set up and interpret the nodes and splits within the tree. I learned how decision trees split the data based on feature thresholds to create decision boundaries that classify the data accurately.

Another interesting concept I came across was the confusion matrix. Creating and interpreting a confusion matrix allowed me to understand the model's performance beyond just accuracy. It provided a clear view of where the model made correct predictions and where it struggled, especially when it came to distinguishing between similar classes like 'versicolor' and 'virginica.'

Finally, I delved into hyperparameter tuning through parameter grid optimization using GridSearchCV. This process was essential to identify the best combination of hyperparameters for my Decision Tree model, thereby improving the model’s accuracy and reducing classification errors. Understanding the concept of parameter grids and how to use them to optimize a model was an eye-opening experience that highlighted the impact of model tuning on performance.
